Abstract = {Twenty-five years since foundational publications on valuing ecosystem
   services for human well-being(1,2), addressing the global biodiversity
   crisis(3) still implies confronting barriers to incorporating nature's
   diverse values into decision-making. These barriers include powerful
   interests supported by current norms and legal rules such as property
   rights, which determine whose values and which values of nature are
   acted on. A better understanding of how and why nature is (under)valued
   is more urgent than ever(4). Notwithstanding agreements to incorporate
   nature's values into actions, including the Kunming-Montreal Global
   Biodiversity Framework (GBF)(5) and the UN Sustainable Development
   Goals(6), predominant environmental and development policies still
   prioritize a subset of values, particularly those linked to markets, and
   ignore other ways people relate to and benefit from nature(7). Arguably,
   a `values crisis' underpins the intertwined crises of biodiversity loss
   and climate change(8), pandemic emergence(9) and socio-environmental
   injustices(10). On the basis of more than 50,000 scientific
   publications, policy documents and Indigenous and local knowledge
   sources, the Intergovernmental Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem
   Services (IPBES) assessed knowledge on nature's diverse values and
   valuation methods to gain insights into their role in policymaking and
   fuller integration into decisions(7,11). Applying this evidence,
   combinations of values-centred approaches are proposed to improve
   valuation and address barriers to uptake, ultimately leveraging
   transformative changes towards more just (that is, fair treatment of
   people and nature, including inter- and intragenerational equity) and
   sustainable futures.},
